    "id": "dcbor-map-int-keys-byte-sort",
    "rule": "D3",
    "rationale": "keys 9 and 10 sort by their 1-byte encoded form (0x09 < 0x0a), not numeric value -- happens to match numeric order here, the point is D3 sorts by bytes, not value. Mirrors rfc8949's P2, same underlying rule.",
    "logical_value": {
      "type": "map",
      "entries": [
        [
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "9"
          },
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "1"
          }
        ],
        [
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "10"
          },
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "2"
          }
        ]
      ]
    },
    "expected_hex": "a209010a02"
  },
  {
    "id": "dcbor-map-int-keys-pure-bytewise-no-length-presort",
    "rule": "D3",
    "rationale": "-24 encodes to 1 byte (0x37); 1000 encodes to 3 bytes (0x1903e8). D3 requires PURE bytewise order with no length pre-sort: 0x19 < 0x37, so the longer encoding of 1000 must sort before the shorter encoding of -24. A length-first (RFC 7049-style) comparator would wrongly sort -24 first.",
    "logical_value": {
      "type": "map",
      "entries": [
        [
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "-24"
          },
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "1"
          }
        ],
        [
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "1000"
          },
          {
            "type": "int",
            "value": "2"
          }
        ]
      ]
    },
    "expected_hex": "a21903e8023701"
  },
  {
